[1] Global as of 16 Mar 2022 - GPEI/WHO cVDPV1 (AFP DR Congo, Nigeria)
Date: Fri 17 Mar 2022
Source: Global Polio Eradication Initiative / WHO [edited]
https://polioeradication.org/polio-today/polio-now/this-week/


Poliovirus weekly update as of 16 Mar 2022, World Health Organization
---------------------------------
New wild poliovirus isolates reported this week:
AFP cases: 0
Environment: 0
Others: 0

New cVDPV isolates reported this week:
AFP cases: 4
Environment: 0
Others: 0

Summary of new polioviruses this week:

-DR Congo: 3 cVDPV2 cases
-Nigeria: 1 cVDPV2 case

Afghanistan

- No new WPV1 or cVDPV2 viruses were reported this week. There is 1 WPV1 case reported in 2022 and 4 in 2021. The total number of cVDPV2 cases remains 43.

Pakistan
- No new WPV1 or cVDPV2 viruses were reported this week. The total number of WPV1 cases in 2021 remains 1. The total number of cVDPV2 cases remains 8.

Benin
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 3 cases reported in 2021.

Burkina Faso
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 2 cases reported in 2021.

Cameroon
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 3 cases reported in 2021.

Central African Republic
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are no cases reported in 2021.

Chad
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are no cases reported in 2021.

Congo (Republic of)
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 2 cases reported in 2021.

Cote d'Ivoire
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are no reported cases in 2021.
- 1 cVDPV2 positive environmental sample was reported in Abidjan 2.

Djibouti
- No cVDPV2 positive environmental samples were reported this week. There are 5 positive environmental samples reported in the country, linked to the virus circulating in Yemen.

Democratic Republic of the Congo (DR Congo)
- 3 cases of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) were reported in Maniema, 1 being from 2021 and 2 from 2022. There are now 3 cases in 2022 and 28 cases from 2021.

Egypt
- No cVDPV2 positive environmental sample was reported this week. There are 11 positive samples reported in 2021.

Ethiopia
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 10 cases reported in 2021.

Gambia
- No cVDPV2 positive environmental samples were reported this week. There are 9 positive samples reported in 2021.

Ghana
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are no cases reported in 2021.

Guinea
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 6 cases in 2021.

Guinea-Bissau
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 3 cases in the country, which are linked to the Jigawa outbreak in Nigeria in 2021.

Israel
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 3 (cVDPV3) was reported this week. There is 1 case reported in the country.

Kenya
- No cVDPV2 positive environmental sample was reported this week. There are 2 cVDPV2 positive environmental samples reported, 1 in 2020 and 1 in 2021. The viruses are linked to the Banadir outbreak in Somalia.

Liberia
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 3 cVDPV2 cases in the country in 2021.

Madagascar
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 1 (cVDPV1) was reported this week. The number of 2021 cases remains 13. There is 1 case in 2022.

Malawi
- No case of WPV1 was reported this week. Last month [February 2022], the country reported the 1st WPV1 case in the continent since 2016.
- In response to confirmation of the WPV1 outbreak in the country, the Government of Malawi declared the outbreak a national public health emergency and activated the emergency operations centre to coordinate outbreak response. Global and regional support from the GPEI Rapid Response Team are in-country to support planning, implementing, and monitoring of response.
- The response plan includes at least 4 large-scale outbreak response campaigns with bivalent OPV, including as part of a subregional, cross-border response together with Mozambique, Tanzania and Zambia, to reach more than 9 million children in the subregion with polio vaccine.
- Training and coordination is ongoing across all levels, including at district levels, to ensure high-quality planning for the upcoming response.
- Health promotion, advocacy, and communication activities are focusing on producing and disseminating high-quality materials, including public service announcements and radio jingles.
- Vaccine distribution and management trainings are underway.
- Surveillance continues to be strengthened, including by supplementing AFP surveillance with roll-out of environmental surveillance, with 8 sites having been established thus far.
- Daily tracking of SIA preparedness across all levels is being coordinated by the emergency operations centre.
- Similar preparations are ongoing in neighbouring countries, including in Tanzania, Zambia, and Mozambique. In Tanzania, for example, training has begun to strengthen microplanning and train vaccinators, social mobilizers, and supervisors. An emergency operations centre has been established to coordinate activities across all levels, focusing on coordination, surveillance, logistics, service delivery, advocacy, communications, social mobilization, and monitoring and evaluation. In Zambia, coordination across all levels is ongoing, to prepare for outbreak response and strengthen surveillance, including by conducting active searches for AFP cases. Environmental sampling will supplement surveillance activities in key areas. Social mobilization activities are being rolled out.

Mali
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. No cases have been reported in 2021.

Mauritania
- No cVDPV2 positive environmental sample was reported this week. There are 7 positive samples linked to the Jigawa outbreak in 2021.

Mozambique
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 2 cases reported in 2021.
- In response to the confirmed cVDPV2 outbreak in the country, the Minister of Health declared the outbreak to be a national public health emergency in February [2022].
- Outbreak response will be implemented, through high-quality SIAs covering the infected provinces. A national emergency operations centre has been established to coordinate outbreak response activities.
- Mozambique will also participate in multi-country, subregional emergency outbreak response with Malawi and other countries, in response to the recent detection of WPV1 in Malawi.
- Surveillance for AFP in high-risk and infected areas is being intensified, supplemented in key areas with environmental surveillance.
- National technical trainings are ongoing to assure highest-possible quality for the upcoming response activities, including at district and provincial levels.
- Social mobilization, mass media, and advocacy activities to ensure community participation is being implemented.
- Vaccine disbursement, including through verification of cold-chain, is ongoing in advance of upcoming campaigns.
- No cVDPV2 positive environmental sample was reported this week. There are 7 positive samples linked to the Jigawa outbreak in 2021.

Niger
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. The number of 2021 cases remains 15.

Nigeria
- 1 case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported in Katsina making it the 3rd case in 2022. The number of 2021 cases remains 415.

Occupied Palestinian territory
- No cVDPV3 positive environmental samples were reported this week. There are 8 ES samples reported in the territory.

Senegal
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 17 cases reported in 2021.

Sierra Leone
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 5 cases reported in 2021.

Somalia
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There is 1 case reported in 2022 and 1 case in 2021.

South Sudan
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 9 cVDPV2 cases reported in 2021.

Sudan
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. No cases have been reported in 2021.

Tajikistan
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 32 cases reported in 2021.

Togo
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. No cases have been reported in 2021.

Uganda
- No cVDPV2 positive environmental sample was reported this week. There are 2 positive samples linked to the N'Djamena outbreak in Chad reported in 2021.

Ukraine
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 2 cases reported in 2021.
- The GPEI is extremely concerned about the unfolding effects of the current crisis in Ukraine on the country's health system. A functioning health system must be kept neutral and protected from all political or security issues affecting countries, to ensure that people have continued access to critical and essential care. At the same time, we have seen time and again that large-scale population movements, insecurity, and hampered access contribute greatly to the emergence and/or spread of infectious diseases, such as polio.
- A national supplemental polio immunization campaign targeting nearly 140 000 children throughout Ukraine who had not been vaccinated against polio began on 1 Feb 2022, but is currently paused, as health authorities have shifted focus towards emergency services. Surveillance to detect and report new cases of polio is also disrupted, increasing the risk of undetected spread of the disease among vulnerable populations. The GPEI is working to urgently develop contingency plans to support Ukraine and prevent further spread of polio. While the cold winter climate of Ukraine is not conducive to polio transmission, undetected residual transmission cannot be ruled out, particularly as the surveillance system has been disrupted.
- The GPEI has a long history of working in a variety of complex environments and will continue to adapt its operations to the reality on the ground, to the degree possible, without compromising on the safety and security of health workers. At the same time, immunization and surveillance is being assessed in neighbouring countries, to minimize the risk and consequences of any potential infectious disease emergence/spread resulting from the current large-scale population movements. It is critical that necessary resources are mobilized and made available to assist with the humanitarian needs, including relief, disease response/prevention efforts both in Ukraine and in neighbouring countries.
- Immunization and surveillance is being assessed in neighbouring countries to minimize the risk and consequences of any potential infectious disease emergence/spread resulting from large-scale population movements.
- The GPEI is strengthening synergies with broader immunization needs for displaced persons, including polio vaccines in the package of health interventions and using polio surveillance to help detect other vaccine-preventable diseases.
- The GPEI is assessing the availability of IPV and measles vaccines in key areas; assessing cold chain capacity and potential impact on it due to electricity cuts; providing communication support for demand generation for immunization; and supporting proactive AFP and environmental surveillance in all IDP sites.
- In border areas, operational support is provided to set up mobile vaccination teams and ensuring safe and efficient transport and temporary storage of vaccines.
- In neighbouring countries (Moldova, Poland, Romania, Slovakia, Hungary), support is focusing on strengthening surveillance (AFP and environmental); registration of children; procurement of vaccines; increase communication to generate vaccine demand; and strengthening immunization in camps and refugee settlements.

Yemen
- No case of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) was reported this week. There are 13 cVDPV2 cases and 3 cVDPV1 cases reported in 2021.

Officially reported WPV1 and cVDPV cases as of 15 Mar 2022
Wild poliovirus (WPV)
- Total global WPV1 cases in 2022: 1 (compared with 2 for the same period in 2021)
- Total global WPV1 cases in 2021: 6

Circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus (cVDPV) cases
- Total global cVDPV cases in 2022: 9 (compared with 31 for the same period in 2021)
- Total global cVDPV cases in 2021: 638

